@page
@model PerformanceOptimization.Pages.IndexModel
@{
    ViewData["Title"] = "Performance Optimization";
}

<section class="hero-card">
    <p class="eyebrow">Performance workflow</p>
    <h1>Optimize EF Core by measuring, inspecting, and simplifying the query.</h1>
    <p class="lead">
        This lesson starts with a deliberately heavy reporting query, then improves it in stages. Students can inspect the generated SQL,
        compare row counts, and see why projection, <code>AsNoTracking()</code>, pagination, and compiled queries matter.
    </p>
    <div class="hero-actions">
        <a class="button-primary" asp-page="/OptimizationLab">Open the optimization lab</a>
        <a class="button-secondary" asp-page="/Products/Index">Open the optimized leaderboard</a>
    </div>
</section>

<section class="grid-panels">
    <article class="panel">
        <h2>What is wrong with the baseline?</h2>
        <p>
            The baseline query loads full <code>Product</code> entities and every related <code>SaleRecord</code>, then performs the ranking in memory.
            That creates unnecessary database reads, larger network payloads, and extra EF Core tracking work.
        </p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
        <h2>How do we improve it?</h2>
        <p>
            We move filtering and aggregation into SQL, project only the fields the page needs, disable tracking for read-only work, and page the results.
            After those bigger wins, we show a compiled query for a repeated hot path.
        </p>
    </article>
    <article class="panel">
        <h2>What should students inspect?</h2>
        <p>
            Read the SQL shown in the lab, then paste it into pgAdmin or Azure Data Studio and run <code>EXPLAIN ANALYZE</code>.
            Compare the work PostgreSQL performs before and after the optimization.
        </p>
    </article>
</section>
